==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Factorial
<hw>Fac*to"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>A name given to the factors of a continued product
when the former are derivable from one and the same function F(x) by
successively imparting a constant increment or decrement <xex>h</xex> to
the independent variable. Thus the product <mathex>F(x).F(x + h).F(x +
2h) . . . F[x + (n-1)h]</mathex> is called a <xex>factorial term</xex>,
and its several factors take the name of <xex>factorials</xex>.</def>
<rj><au>Brande & C.</au></rj></p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The product of the consecutive whole numbers from
unity up to any given number; <as>thus, 5 <ex>factorial</ex> is the
product of 5 times four times three times two times one, or
120</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Factoring</ent>⟦br⟧
